<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-147-264  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 147 264.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  Feb 7 1990 n1494 p11(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The domino effect.(budget cuts at British Telecom will affect itssuppliers as well)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilson, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>British Telecom (BT), Britain's second largest commercialbusiness, must operate efficiently and competitively.andP;  This oftenentails budget cuts, which affect not only BT, but its suppliersand contractors as well.andP;  A round of budget cuts is taking placeat BT currently, triggered by an attempt to trim spending in 1990by 600 million pounds sterling.andP;  Some 200 suppliers of networkcomponents and materials have had their orders frozen until April,1990, while stock on hand is reduced to more manageable levels.andO;An industry analyst believes the problem is part of a cycle.andP;  BToverorders to compensate for suppliers' inability to meet deliverycommitments, then cuts back when suppliers improve output and BTbecomes overstocked.andP;  BT is also believed to be looking at ways ofreducing its staff of over 100,000 full-time employees by 20percent through attrition and subcontracting of non-coreactivities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   British Telecommunications PLC (management).andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsBudgetingManagementEnglandManufacturers.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>